@weijietong Thanks for the contribution.  We've spent some time looking at it and have wanted something similar to happen in order to enable us to switch from using `ByteBuffer` to using something based on `Unsafe` which should be significantly faster (generally things tend to run in 2/3 the time).

In looking at the interfaces, there are a few things that we expect to have real performance implications (one example is the proposal to move everything to big endian, that will actually end up slowing down speeds by about 3x or 4x).  In general, it is important to use native endianness when working with memory mapped files.

We are putting together a counter proposal that would actually return the datasketches `Memory` interface instead of the `DataInput` and `DataOutput` interfaces that you borrowed from Lucene.  The hope is that the `Memory` interface will be a bit more in-line with the needs of data processing, hopefully it is also something you can implement on top of your distributed filesystem implementation.

@weijietong Yeah, you are right, a lot of the stuff is using big-endian values.  That wasn't intentional though, it was a historical accident (I didn't realize it until I spent a bit of time trying to read segments with `Unsafe`...).  Given the known performance differences between native endianess and non-native, I'd prefer not to enshrine that mistake and instead work to fix it in future versions.

Fwiw, the `Memory` interface I'm talking about is at https://github.com/DataSketches/sketches-core/blob/master/memory/src/main/java/com/yahoo/memory/Memory.java

It has an implementation that uses `Unsafe`, but should also be individually implementable to not use `Unsafe`.  For now, we are looking at if it would be possible to return a `Memory` from the `Directory` object.

