@weijietong I can see that you have put a great deal of effort into this proposal and your work is greatly appreciated!

Unfortunately, the devil is in the details.

The position, limit, mark, flip, rewind (PLMFR) concepts in ByteBuffer are there to enable efficient alternating write / read sequences for IO streams of bytes, for example using TCP/IP sockets. TCP/IP specifies Big-Endian for the transmission elements, like source/destination address, port, etc, but the endianness for the payload is up to the higher layers.

The fact that ByteBuffer uses Big-Endian as the default is historical and likely tied to its early use with socket streams or because Sun used SPARC CPUs. Note that the default for an allocated or wrapped LongBuffer is Native-Order and cannot be changed, while a LongBuffer view inherits its endianness from the parent ByteBuffer.

Today, Little-Endian is the default for virtually all large systems (Intel and AMD CPUs). The fact that folks did not bother to specify Native-Endian for reading and writing into memory and memory-mapped files is indeed unfortunate as it is very inefficient.

The PLMFR concepts in ByteBuffer get in the way if you want to efficiently and arbitrarily read and write arrays and fields into packed data structures in memory or memory-mapped files. 

Consider a toy packed structure similar to: 

    typedef struct {       //offsets
        int intArr[8]      //0
        long longArr[8];   //32
        double dblsArr[8]; //96
    } byteArr

And the task is to write these 3 arrays in reverse order:

With ByteBuffer:

    ByteBuffer bb = ByteBuffer.wrap(byteArr);
    bb.order(ByteOrder.LITTLE_ENDIAN);
    
    bb.position(96);
    DoubleBuffer db = bb.asDoubleBuffer();
    db.put(dblsArr, 0, 8);
    
    bb.position(32);
    LongBuffer lb = bb.asLongBuffer();
    lb.put(longArr, 0, 8);
    
    bb.position(0);
    IntBuffer ib = bb.asIntBuffer();
    ib.put(intArr, 0, 8);

With Memory:

    Memory mem = new NativeMemory(byteArr);
    mem.putDoubleArray(96, dblsArr, 0, 8);
    mem.putLongArray(32, longArr, 0, 8);
    mem.putIntArray(0, intArr, 0, 8);

The ByteBuffer approach requires the creation of 3 additional objects and 3 changes to position!
Each of the Memory calls are directly tied to a single Unsafe call, which is converted to CPU intrinsics by the JIT compiler.

The Memory package also allows wrapping a ByteBuffer for backward compatibility:

    Memory mem = new NativeMemory(byteBuffer);

This allows simultaneous views of a region in memory from the ByteBuffer or from Memory.
For those cases where the PLMFR concepts are really required or the historical data was inadvertently written Big-Endian, the user can choose the ByteBuffer view.  New applications could use Memory directly, thus provide for a gradual transition away from the Big-Endian assumptions as well as away from the ByteBuffer entirely.

Memory enables creating memory regions and mapped files larger than 2 GB, and for the really critical performance cases, Memory allows direct access to the Unsafe class, all caveats hereby included :)

Unsafe (and thus Memory) are intentionally only Native-Endian for performance reasons. 

***
I do not consider the proposed DataInput / DataOutput and IndexInput / IndexOutput to be similar to Memory at all. Instead, the DataInput / DataOutput classes could wrap or include Memory objects and have access to a very rich (and fast) API for reading & writing all the primitive types and their corresponding arrays, access to large (> 2GB) off-heap memory and memory-mapped files, and dual views into ByteBuffers if required. 

As @cheddar pointed out, the current assumption of Big-Endian would continue the performance pain going forward. Unfortunately, specifying a Byte-Order parameter for every primitive read/write call would be a performance killer.

I would like to propose that we work together to find a solution for Druid going forward. I would be glad to help you understand the Memory package and how to efficiently use it, and if some extensions to the Memory package is really required, it is open for discussion!

@leerho thanks for your idea. I am not insisting on my propose. I want to point out that as you gave examples : 
```
Memory mem = new NativeMemory(byteArr);
mem.putDoubleArray(96, dblsArr, 0, 8);
mem.putLongArray(32, longArr, 0, 8);
mem.putIntArray(0, intArr, 0, 8);
```
it's hard to give out the values like `0 , 32 , 96` relative to current Druid codes, and I agree NativeMemory may save some cpu instructions through using `Unsafe` ,but I think `NativeMemory` is a specific storage implementation eg memory. so what about other storage implementations like hdfs ,which only operates byte stream oriented ,then `Unsafe` can not give any help.

So I want to point out that we are now defining a interface A ,then we implement that interface A ,and utilize some performance better techs like `mmap` ,`Unsafe` ,`native ByteBuffer`.

I would also be pleasure to see that we find out a better solution to let Druid run on different storage platforms without too pain refactor works . It's open for discussion too , everybody!

